{
  "title": "Dopamine and Eureka Moments",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f656b14224753a54",
      "text": "There is some evidence to suggest that dopamine and other neurotransmitters may be released during an \"Aha!\" moment, which can occur at the moment of a Bayesian belief update."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2cab5ee83c221223",
      "text": "\nThe exact neural mechanisms underlying these moments of insight and belief updates are still not completely understood, but research suggests that dopamine may play a role in modulating the brain's reward and motivation systems, which could be involved in generating these experiences.\n\nOne study found that activity in the dopamine system was increased during moments of insight, as measured by electroencephalography (EEG) recordings of the brain. Another study showed that dopamine release in the striatum, a brain region associated with reward processing, was associated with successful problem solving and learning from feedback.\n\nOther neurotransmitters, such as serotonin and norepinephrine, have also been implicated in modulating cognitive processes related to insight and belief updates. However, further research is needed to fully understand the role of neurotransmitters in these processes."
    }
